LAYER 3: EXTRACTION AND SELECTION
how Fadriel sees which part of the grid IS the answer

observe spatial_perception.rana

many puzzles ask: "which piece matters?"
the output is SMALLER than the input
the answer is hidden INSIDE the input
Fadriel must learn to SELECT the right piece

@spatial_rule extract_unique
CHECK output is smaller than input
DETECT all clusters in input
FIND the cluster that is UNIQUE: different color, shape, or size from others
EXTRACT bounding box around the unique cluster
VERIFY extracted region matches output for all training pairs
APPLY extract unique region from test input
SPEECH "I extract the unique shape"

@spatial_rule extract_interior
CHECK output is smaller than input
DETECT a frame or border in the input
EXTRACT the region INSIDE the frame
VERIFY interior matches output for all pairs
APPLY extract interior from test input
SPEECH "I extract what's inside the frame"

@spatial_rule extract_by_marker
CHECK output is smaller than input  
DETECT a marker color in the input (small dot or single cell)
EXTRACT region around or near the marker
VERIFY extraction matches output
APPLY extract region near marker in test
SPEECH "the marker tells me where to look"

@spatial_rule extract_by_overlap
CHECK output is smaller than input
DETECT multiple overlapping shapes in input
EXTRACT the region where shapes overlap
VERIFY overlap matches output
APPLY find and extract overlap in test
SPEECH "the answer is where shapes overlap"

@spatial_rule select_by_count
CHECK output is 1x1 or very small
DETECT countable features in input (shapes, colors, cells)
COUNT the relevant feature
OUTPUT the count as a grid value
VERIFY count matches output for all pairs
APPLY count and output for test
SPEECH "I count {n} and that's the answer"

@spatial_rule select_by_majority
CHECK output is smaller than input
DETECT multiple candidate regions
SELECT the one with the most cells, or most unique color
VERIFY selection matches output
APPLY select majority region in test
SPEECH "the biggest one is the answer"

the key to extraction:
the output is not a TRANSFORMATION of the input
it is a SELECTION from the input
nothing changes color or moves
something gets CHOSEN
the question is: what is the selection criterion?

possible criteria:
- uniqueness (the one that's different)
- containment (what's inside the frame)
- proximity (what's near the marker)
- overlap (where things cross)
- counting (how many of something)
- majority (the biggest group)

@perceive extraction
DETECT output smaller than input
DETECT output content exists somewhere in input
FIND where in input the output content appears
LEARN what distinguished that region
